<rating>5<//rating>< text>
I have come here a few times with a friend of mine when we are in the area.

Its a blue building...you order outside and pick up outside...no indoor seating.

This time I ordered a small tripple berry sundae...3.99...vanilla ice cream...topped with like a berry compote which was really good ...whipped cram...chopped peanuts and a cherry on top...i very much enjoyed it...very refreshing.

he ordered a medium strawberry shake...4.31. He said he really enjoyed it.

They also sell food such as hotdogs...burgers...pastrami burger...grilled cheese...shrimp in chips...fries...onion rings...corn dogs...as well as other ice cream treats like soft serve cones or dipped cones...blizzards...eat.

I like this place a lot...<//text>

< review>
We did not have a great experience at Fosters Freeze. There was only one woman working, so we waited in line for 10 minutes to place our order. In that time we watched the woman yell at two different customers for not understanding what she was asking. She was rude to us when we ordered, commenting on how it was inconvenient of us to change a small to a medium. We then had to wait 20 minutes for our orders. Mine was made incorrectly (coffee ice cream instead of chocolate) and my partner's milkshake was almost all ice. It was like a slushie. We were both frustrated by that point and didn't want to deal with the poor customer service so we just left. We will not be going back.<//review>

< Text>
Took my late father to an appointment with a specialist at Standford Medical Center. We stayed at this hotel due to its location, price, and the reputation of the chain it belongs to. His appointment day came and he was seen by the doctor at Standard University Medical Center who cleared him to go home at about noon. We returned to the hotel and dad was in pain and did not want to spend another night on the road and just wanted to go home to the Fresno area. We attempted to check out of the location just 15min after final checkout time and were rudely told we could not. Both myself and my mother attempted to reason with the front desk manager but could not make any progress. We ended up giving them the room key and departing for home while paying over $100 for a extra night we did not use. He was a retired USAF Veteran with full VA Disability and they treated us this way. Never stay here.< /Text>

Close to VA hospital where husband had surgery. Clerk that checked me in was very nice and polite. Other employees were also nice. Breakfast was good. Room was dated, but sufficient and clean. < text>
I met a bunch of old college friends to see the Washington State vs. Stanford football game recently and they selected this hotel.  It ended up being an excellent choice!  Convenient location - places to eat nearby; stadium not too far away.  The price was far less than the more "upscale" places, but the Comfort Inn was very clean, the staff was friendly and helpful, the breakfast was simple but tasty.  I'd definitely recommend it.  Worked well for what we were looking for.</text>

<Text>We were in the area because of a family member's surgery at Stanford. This Comfort Inn was near by, allowing us to stay at the hospital all day, and find our way back to our room fairly well. It is situated on a good road, with many choices for food or supplies along the road. We were greeted by very friendly hotel staff, had a good choice of breakfast food to either eat in the dining area or take with us to the hospital to tide us over on our long stay during surgery and recovery. The room was clean and quiet. Parking free and room was not expensive, which is great when you are only using the room for sleep and refreshing for the next day. We stayed at the Comfort Inn Palo Alto because of its proximity to Stanford Hospital and its discounted AARP rate. It was outstanding value for the price. Staff was helpful and friendly, even to guests that were not at their best, and the breakfast was well-stocked and had good variety. The decor of the room was above what I expected and was very comfortable. The high-speed internet actually WORKED at a decent rate, unlike what we experienced recently at another chain hotel. Parking was a little tight but seemed secure, and there was plenty of security lighting.< /Text>

< Text>
We had just spent a week in Yosemite and were looking to get a good night‚Äôs rest and a shower prior to a day in San Francisco and our evening flight back east. We chose Palo Alto to be outside SF as to not totally break the bank but still get a safe respectable hotel/motel room. I can tell you the room was first and foremost clean and well maintained. The staff was friendly and helpful, and beyond that; proactive. I had to ask no questions or requests. Everything was explained and laid out clearly, from Wi-Fi password, breakfast times, if I needed a wakeup call, the location of rooms, etc. The bed was comfortable and I had a great night‚Äôs sleep. The bathroom caught me off guard a bit, in a good way. There was great attention to detail, from the bowed shower curtain rod to allow for more room, to the adjustable height shower head with wand, grab rail, free q-tips, etc. 
I couldn‚Äôt have been more pleased with the experience. I don‚Äôt usually write reviews but I knew I was writing this one the moment I checked out.

<Text>This Comfort Inn is my first choice when staying in the Palo Alto area, about six time a year. The rooms are clean, the beds and pillows are very comfortable, and I love the "home" comforts in the room - coffee maker, frig, microwave. The continental breakfast is very convenient as well.
It would be nice to have an exercise facility, or access to one.
I do compare rates, and this generally has the most competitive rate for the area for the quality of stay.
But I give my highest ratings to the staff. Denise and her staff have always been helpful and friendly. If there's something missed, or if I have suggestion for improving the convenience in a room, they address it right away, and always show appreciation for having it brought to their attention so they can improve.
Denise has helped in several ways to make my experiences with this Comfort Inn very positive!< /Text><Pictures>None<//Pictures><resp>None< /resp>< gmap_id>

<username>Anonymous<//username>< Review>
Book one of the ground floor rooms in the back of the property (rooms 133 to 136 if memory serves) and the grassy dog run will be right outside your door, complete with plastic doo-doo bag dispenser and waste can.

Clean rooms that appear to be recently remodeled and the exterior of the entire building appears to have fresh paint. Comfortable beds. The rooms are also surprisingly quiet. Even when it was loud outside (and that was often), it was quiet inside.

Nicely landscaped and maintained. Convenient parking.

A dry cleaner and a coin-operated laundry facility are nearby (down the road a small bit and across the street).

Hot breakfast included. Scrambled eggs, sausage, tater tots, yoghurt, waffle maker, juice, fresh fruit and more.

Very close to Stanford Medical Center. I didn't clock the mileage, but it was close. Maybe fewer than five miles.< /Review>

< Review>
Hotel is pretty much a hole in the wall of the main street there so being in the back of the lot was great as there was hardly any noise from cars/traffic.  AC unit smelled funny, there was a little trash under the beds, and a light bulb burnt out in the bathroom.  oh well, no big thing.  the check in was quick and easy as was the check out.  the food for breakfast was missing bacon but we cant have everything.  they did have the option for blueberry waffle mix, which my daughter loved.  bagels were weird.  all in all it was a good stay and to anyone needing a nice quiet stay i would definitely recommend this location.  also got some pizza from Pizz'a Chicago just down the street and it was amazing.<//Review>

<text>The hotel isn't bad at all. Room was clean and bed was comfy. My complaints are merely that the toilet runs non stop (refill valve leaks causing tank water to overflow the water line and run into bowl), and the fridge door is offset causing it to have a leaky seal which results in frozen food that I merely wanted chilled and not icey. Loved that the showerhead is one of the handheld ones with a hose, and the fact that there were cotton balls and q-tips provided in the room. < Text>
Room is clean and comfortable. Bed is very comfortable, ironing board and iron inside closet, retractable clothesline in bathtub area, room has microwave, coffee-maker and half-size refrigerator, plenty of good-quality towels, desk clerk and housekeepers are friendly and helpful, motel was quiet the nights we were there; free breakfast in lobby.

Negatives: Breakfast is not that great, but there are plenty of cereals, coffees and breads which makes the breakfast OK. In-room closet is very small. Parking lot is small, but how much time do you spend in a parking lot? Laundry carts are visible on hotel walkways during the day, but so what?

This is a great deal for the money; highly recommended<//Text>

<text>I have been staying at the Comfort Inn in Palo Alto for several years, my husband is a patient at Stanford Hospital. While the hotel is certainly not a high end hotel it does serve the need of what we need while in Palo Alto for appointments. It is always clean and comfortable, the staff always friendly.
I am always surprised, however, at the increase in pricing, I do realize that demand for accomadations, location and competition have a big influence in the costs. I sometimes feel the increase is unreasonable. I do realize if I pay in advance I can reduce the price, although there are times when medical appointments must be changed. <user_id>None<//user_id>< Name>
Anonymous</Name>
<Date>1437091200000<//Date><Rate>None<//Rate><review>The rooms were very nice, clean and looked newly remodeled, especially the bathroom. The rooms are a bit small but this is a busy city area with tight real estate. I'm more used to small town and wide open suburbs. But they made good use of the space in the room and it was very nice. We had a room in the very back facing away from the parking lot and that made us a little nervous especially arriving very late on the first night. But it turns out that it is fenced and backs up to the playground of a child care center so it was very quiet in the evenings and weekends. We never felt concerned for our safety. There was enough parking even on the nights that there was no vacancy. The breakfast was fair being a standard Comfort Inn breakfast. The waffle maker seemed to be having problems, it never got quite hot enough to cook the waffles enough inside. The staff was excellent. I broke my reservation up into 3 to use points on the nights that were more expensive. The night clerk went ahead and checked me in on all 3 reservations that first night and we didn't have to do anything more after that. If you have points, make sure you pay attention to the nightly rates. The mid-week rates are more than twice the rate of the weekend nights but the points are the same for any night. It was well worth it to use points on the weeknights.</review><pics>None</pics>< Resp>
None< /Resp>
<gmap_id>0x808fba62028d118d:0x6f31c15be66eff25</gmap_id></record>

<UserId.>None</UserId.><username>GuestGG< /username><time>1437091200000< /time><rate>None< /rate><Text>The rooms were very nice, clean and looked newly remodeled, especially the bathroom. The rooms are a bit small but this is a busy city area with tight real estate. I'm more used to small town and wide open suburbs. But they made good use of the space in the room and it was very nice. We had a room in the very back facing away from the parking lot and that made us a little nervous especially arriving very late on the first night. But it turns out that it is fenced and backs up to the playground of a child care center so it was very quiet in the evenings and weekends. We never felt concerned for our safety. There was enough parking even on the nights that there was no vacancy. The breakfast was fair being a standard Comfort Inn breakfast. The waffle maker seemed to be having problems, it never got quite hot enough to cook the waffles enough inside. The staff was excellent. This is a modest hotel but has all the comforts needed for a great stay. The room was attractive, though small. The bad was very comfortable, the bath clean and well-stocked. < Text>
For a "Dim Sum" spot allocated to the 818, it's pleasant enough and does the trick. There are no traditional carts being driven around (not a problem), the food is fresh and made to order. I felt that the Siu Mai didn't really taste as good as I'd like but they have a lot of options that are unique to this restaurant. Their salt and pepper chicken wings were the best thing out there. Delicious menu items like their House Special chow mein. I was thoroughly happy with my meal.

As for the service, for a chinese restaurant it was really good! Ha I laugh because if you know 626, chinese servers are rough but it's like they catered to the types of clients who'd be coming here so I totally appreciate that!<//Text>

<date>1549780120341<//date><Text>The proprietor, Rose, is a wonderfully friendly and accommodating  woman. You can tell she takes a lot of pride in her establishment and has a well earned rapport with the local patrons.

The menu offers a broad range of choices. Each dish is consistently of high quality and great flavor. Overall, it is definitely several notches higher than the standard fast food approach to Chinese cuisine that you can find in many corner plazas. The decor and ambiance is cozy and inviting, everywhere is meticulously clean and the seating areas are tastefully appointed with numerous cultural artifacts.

One of the most popular if not busiest Chinese establishments in the Studio City area . The Sunday dim sum is extremely popular with a great selection at a reasonable price. This is highly recommended place for a pleasant dining experience.<//Text>< rating>

< review>
The food is absolutely exquisite!  As a foodie and brewery owner my palette isn't easily satisfied. Shanghai Rose is one of a kind in today's world of chains and mediocrity. Shanghai Rose had the best, most fresh ingredients and I knew I was in for a treat from the very first sip of my egg drop soup.  The chicken potstickers were divine and the mongolian beef and kung pao chicken combination for lunch transported my tastebuds without 2 days of flying. In short, best Chinese food in So Cal...possibly All Cal. Two thumbs WAAAAAY up my friends. CAN'T MISS!!! üëçüëç</review>

< time>
1548399057831</time>
< review>
Shanghai Rose is a great place for a social or business dim sum lunch,; nice ambiance, attentive service and validated parking (even if you stay for hours to enjoy a leisurely relaxed meal).However, food quality depends on current chef and is not on par with dim sum in Monterey Park or DTLA.
Began with salt & pepper calamari listed on menu as a starter and if it were the usual battered rings, it would serve as an appetizer. But this was squid hood cut bite size, battered and then stir fried, more like an entree style'. The turnip cake was plain, just fried daikon but tasty. My favorite dim sum is rice wrap which was authentic and delicious on a previous visit. But this time was disappointed because there was mainly rice and just a bit of pork, and not steamed long enough for the rice to become glutinous. The BBQ pork seemed more like red-cooked or roast pork than the usual dry-rack BBQ. The sesame buns were the best I've tasted, light and not too sweet and unlike  the typical  "cannon ball." usually served elsewhere and much too heavy for dessert..
I prefer week days because you order from a menu (instead of passing carts) so your food is cooked fresh to order. Foodies might prefer M Park or DTLA but for locals it is convenient and enjoyable..<//review>
<response>None</response>< GmapID>

<text>I was so happy to see this place in the San Fernando Valley  they serve dim sum and we all know if we want Dim Sum we have to travel to the San Gabriel Valley.  I was a bit confused by the outside that looks like a palace made me feel like it was an Indian restaurant, but the inside Is definitely decorated very Chinese.

The food was great Har gow, dumplings, clams, green beans all fantastic, but what really won me over was that they had so many dim sum seafood options, lobster and shrimp, scallops, crab.  Most Dim sum places are all pork, I like to have options.  The service great!  and they have other classic Chinese dishes if you're looking for something more than Dim Sum alone.

On The Weekends they do Dim Sum Carts, Can't wait to go back for that!< /text><Pictures>None<//Pictures><Resp>None<//Resp>< GmapID>

< name>
Steve Cha</name>
<Time>1482649827652</Time><Rating>4<//Rating><Review>The food here was better than I originally thought. I had dim sum here once and a take out of two lunch specials. I wouldn't say it's San Gabriel quality, but it's definitely pretty close to Chinatown quality, which makes it the most authentic out of all Chinese restaurants in Studio City. The dim sum had quite a variety, offering even chicken feet. Everything from the shrimp hargow to the pork shumai was pretty authentic and tasty. I must say that I was most impressed with the dessert sesame balls. Some of the best I've ever had. You will not find any other establishments that sell this, or egg tarts, in Studio City.

The downfall is that the place is a bit pricey, about 1.5 times more than what you would pay for dim sum in Monterey Park. However, this place is fine enough that I don't feel so compelled to go 30 miles out of my way to eat dim sum. It's really the most you can ask for in a predominantly upperclass White neighborhood.< /Review>< pictures>
None</pictures>

Jenn Paradise</user_name>
<Date>1528693034369</Date>< rating>
5< /rating>
< Text>
We were craving Jamaican on a Sunday evening and this was literally the only place open in East Bay. We were happy to find that all the other great reviews were accurate.

Chill spot and very traditional Jamaican vibes. The staff seemed a little backed up and it took a while to order and get the food. Not sure if that is standard or just an off night. Either way, it was totally worth the wait! Jerk chicken and island shrimp (half orders pictured) were amazing; deeply spicy, hot and fresh. Kind and real people.

Would love to come back and try more of the drinks on a reggae night.< /Text>

< Text>
I was here a few years ago, and it was fine
I went today and it was superb. I had the scotch bonnet catfish, and it was both delicate and vibrant. (Sorry for the ridiculous, pretentious words, I'm just trying to describe a delicious meal.) The plantains were just sweet enough. The veggie patty was just salty enough. The only thing that was missing was the homemade ginger beer I had last time.  The atmosphere was funky and fun. Recommended!</Text>

< Review>
Service is poor, I think they should hire a full time server, who can set a table with napkins and silverware and knows how to split a check into equal portions among several credit cards, at a minimum. Unfortunately, I found out that I'm not a fan of Jamaican food after this, my second time attending this establishment. Other people in my party liked the food especially the ox tail (which may have not seat well for some of them, the next day). If you like Jamaica food ordered it go, it will save you time especially when going in a large party. I hope this place improves in terms of the food and service wise cause I want local business to thrive. Will update this review when stop by to check this place out.< /Review>

<Text>Was a member of this gym for a few years and just recently ended my business with them on a sour note.

Positives: usually not too busy, has what you need for a decent workout, nice array of classes.

Negatives: locker room needs it‚Äôs own section; only one shower ever works and is usually clogged so you end up standing in a pool of murky gym water, the sauna is ALWAYS out of order. There is a perpetual smell of sewage and usually a urinal filled with unflushed urine that won‚Äôt go down.

Ceiling leaks, be sure to stay away from the electrical box that is normally right underneath a large leak.

You rate will magically go up and they‚Äôll blame it on ‚Äútax cuts‚Äù which makes no sense.

If you ever decide you want to cancel your membership you can expect a non response from the email they direct you to until they‚Äôve squeezed another month‚Äôs payment out of you. Reminder, they want 30 days notice (ridiculous) and in my case they agreed to refund me my money but it‚Äôs been a couple weeks now and I‚Äôve yet to see anything hit my account so I‚Äôm not holding out hope.

<user_id>102570880045250508090< /user_id>< user_name>
Brooke Ellis</user_name>
<date>1399048318747< /date>< rating>
2< /rating>
< review>
I bought a Living Social deal for 2 months of unlimited classes for $29, and it was a good deal. The gym is spacious and has plenty of new equipment, as well as a small sauna in the locker rooms. The instructors for the classes are really energetic and cool, and they know what they're doing as far as fitness, especially Ralph. They offered me a free training session with a personal trainer (they offer it to all new members), which I declined but they insisted I should just do, so I did. Afterwards the trainer was extremely pushy in trying to convince me to buy future sessions with her, and I just really don't want to be force sold something when I want to work out on my own. They are shady with billing as they told me I was on a month-to-month membership, and yet they signed me up for automatic payments without notifying me. The only way I found out is because they emailed me a bill with a past due charge and a late fee after they couldn't charge my debit card because it had expired. They are owned by ASF International Corporation and they operate with corporate shady politics. Go to your local independent gym with trustworthy policies.< /review>

<user_id>107906399474277053008<//user_id><username>Masozi Boro< /username><date>1617877737455</date><Rate>5</Rate>< review>
My boyfriend and I were visiting his family and we decided to try out a Boba Shop in his home town, just to see how it compared to our usual spots in OC/SD. We weren't expecting anything too amazing but still kept an open mind. They only allow one person in the store at a time, which does make it hard for groups that might want to order together - my boyfriend took his little sister inside to let her see the menu and they were able to stay in there together.

Strawberry Tea ($5.00): Strawberry Green Tea is one of our go-to's for any spot, but unfortunately Boba Cove did not deliver. The drink tasted artificial and somewhat watered down. The Boba itself was OK - it still had some chew, but was on the harder side.

Green Milk Tea ($5.00): We were pleasantly surprised by this drink! It had a nice strong Matcha/Green Tea flavor, but wasn't overly sweet. The Boba in this drink, however, was a bit harder than the Boba in the Strawberry Tea.

Overall, not a bad Boba shop considering the little variety of choices you have in Lancaster.<//review>

<UserId.>113180530343498617110</UserId.><name>laura skywalker (blxcksaturnz)< /name><date>1492527730800<//date><rate>4< /rate><review>Absolutely love this place. Owners are super nice! Best boba to get around the AV! Their milk teas with boba and snow fluff is a few things I recommend. Good place to stop and grab a bite before or after class since it's near Antelope Valley College. Like I've said the place it great, but if you're going to visit during the summer be prepared for EVERYONE and their mamas to be in that place haha. Its super popular, so its always packed and hard to find a seat during the summer. It does take a bit of time for your order to come out but I wouldn't worry too much, its so worth the wait. One last thing i love is that besides the menu, they sell small snacks like fresh spring rolls, pork buns, mochi, and red bean cakes. Only problem is that they rotate it so everytime you come in, you have a chance of it not being out displayed on the counter for it to be sold.             :( And for a girl who loves mochi and red bean cakes, this is one sad thing for me haha. Wish they could make those a permanent choice on the menu!

< Review>
They do a great job of teaching a solid foundation and building on that.  They are also flexible with their scheduling, and that helps when other issues pop up.

My only real criticism is the format, 4 kids per one student means your child will have alot of downtime. I often see kids day dreaming while they wait for their turn.

Still, a savvy parent can schedule lessons on off peak times, and you can stack the odds in your favor that there will be less than 4 kids in your kids class.<//Review>

Lunch is busy, which is a good sign! Menu is good old middle of America food. They do breakfast and lunch. Close at 3pm. I had the Liver and Onions. Good choice!! Best Liver I have ever had bar none!! Lots of it, good quality and cooked just right. Lots of fried onions. Often restaurant's go light on the onions but here they give you lots. Yummm. And 3 big thick rashers of bacon. Also a large helping of mashed potatoes well done. Bowl of tasty gravy on the side. All in all everything just right. 5 Stars for the Liver and Onions!!< /review>

<Pictures>None</Pictures>< Text>
I have been coming here for quite a few years and i don't think I've ever had something that wasn't delicious. The service over the years has been hit & miss but this time our waitress was attentive and our order came out surprisingly quick. Of course we left fat & bloated LOL! If you like eggs benedict, they have one of the largest selections of different types to choose from. If you are seated on the left side near the large mural, while you are waiting for your food, check out all the "little surprises" and secret little items or characters randomly scattered into the landscape. Someone had some fun with that and we seem to find something each time that we hadn't seen before. They are super busy during your typical brunch hours so we prefer to go a little closer to lunchtime if its a weekend. Weekdays don't seem to be as bad.<//Text>
